    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>HPV Vaccination For Schoolgirls</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>New York Assemblywoman Amy Paulin letter on Sigrid Fry-Revere's March 25 Op-Ed article supports school-based immunization of girls against human papillomavirus</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Rush to Vaccinate,'' by Sigrid Fry-Revere (Op-Ed, March 25):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Rush to Vaccinate,'' by Sigrid Fry-Revere (Op-Ed, March 25):</p>
        <p>The world's first cancer vaccine has the potential to prevent thousands of new cases of cervical cancer each year. In New York, 1,000 women will be diagnosed and 300 will die from cervical cancer this year. More than 99 percent of cervical cancer cases are linked to the human papillomavirus (HPV). The Food and Drug Administration approved a vaccine to protect against HPV, and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommended vaccination of girls 11 and 12 years of age.</p>
        <p>When the C.D.C. has recommended a vaccination for school-age children, New York has added it to the list of required school vaccinations. Vaccination against hepatitis B, a sexually transmitted disease, and tetanus, caused by wound contamination, are mandated.</p>
        <p>Mandated vaccination will reduce cervical cancer within underserved populations, which are disproportionately affected by cervical cancer because of lack of access to affordable health services.</p>
        <p>Because the vaccine is most effective when given before being infected, girls should be vaccinated before sexual activity. Since school dropout rates rise at age 13, middle school is, according to the Guttmacher Policy Review, ''the last public health gate that an entire age-group of individuals pass through together -- regardless of race, ethnicity or socioeconomic status.''</p>
        <p>School-based immunization is the only effective way to achieve widespread immunization and close racial, ethnic and socioeconomic gaps in immunization rates.</p>
        <p>Amy Paulin  Scarsdale</p>
        <p>The writer is a New York State assemblywoman, 88th District.</p>
      </block>
